text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Te Reo Māori%0a%0a:Author: shsin%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aMāori, the native language of New Zealand, is still endangered after over four decades of work to revive it%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aTe Reo Māori, the native language of New Zealand, became endangered as a result of colonization. Early English settlers in New Zealand learned Māori (1), but as Europeans became the majority around the 1860s, English became the dominant language. Children were encouraged to speak English in the community and some were even punished for speaking Māori in schools. More Māori people also began moving from rural communities to cities, where English was widely spoken, particularly during World War 2 (2). In the 1930s, 96%25 of Māori families spoke the Māori language. By the 1960s, only 26%25 still spoke it. %0a%0aIn 1972, a petition was presented to the New Zealand Parliament to have the Māori language and culture taught in schools. New Zealand also established Māori language week in the 1970s and made Māori an official language in 1987. Particularly over the last couple of decades, the use of Māori has become normalized in New Zealand with presenters speaking in Māori on television and candy and peanut butter companies adding Māori to their product labels (3). Particularly over the last decade, interest in learning Māori has grown among young people, both Māori and non-Māori. Between 2018 and 2022, the proportion of people able to speak "more than a few words or phrases" of Māori rose from 24%25 to 30%25. %0a%0aHowever, some experts have concerns that the widespread interest in the Māori language might actually be harming revival efforts. A recently-published study, which compared Māori to Welsh (a language that has successfully reversed its decline in Wales) argued that Māori might be on a "pathway towards extinction" and that Māori education should be prioritized for Māori children to avoid stretching the limited pool of qualified Māori teachers too thin (4). %0a%0a(1) https://te-pa-tu.com/our-stories/the-fascinating-history-of-new-zealands-native-language/%0a(2) https://nzhistory.govt.nz/culture/maori-language-week/history-of-the-maori-language%0a(3) https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2022/09/m-ori-language-week-expert-says-new-zealand-doing-better-than-rest-of-world-at-revitalising-protecting-indigenous-language.html%0a(4) https://time.com/5922833/new-zealand-maori-language/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221103-182008-619990#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Māori language %0a-> - hyunsunb%0a-> [-03.11.2022 - 11:20-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221103-182008-619990 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe Māori language has a distinctive aspect of the language where there are long and short vowels. The long vowels are indicated with the dash over the letter (as shown in "Māori"). Instead of typing "Maaori," it then would be "Māori."%0aMāori has a specific syllabic structure of (C)V(V): V, VV, CV, CVV. CV combinations of "wo, who, wu, and whu" mostly happen in loanwords from English.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221103-182008-619990#%0a#foxbegin 221204-225951-345560#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Why Māori Language Will Struggle to Persist Despite Revitalization Efforts %0a-> - johnternullo%0a-> [-04.12.2022 - 14:59-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221204-225951-345560 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aPākehā (non-Māori) children of New Zealand have begun to learn the Māori language in schools with support of the government, which is aiming for at least 150,000 proficient speakers and 1,000,000 speakers at a basic level by the year 2040. According to models, the number of Māori language speakers may actually decline despite these efforts, due to the future lack of qualified teachers. That is, teaching Pākehā people who will not pass down the language in any way may be an inefficient use of resources relative to providing quality language education for nearly all Māori people. However, anyone can contribute to ensuring the language continues to be spoken by learning and using it. Another obstacle to the language's preservation is that a smaller proportion of speakers are under the age of 65, making less certain the future of how widely-used the language will be.%0a%0ahttps://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/01/m-ori-language-likely-doomed-despite-recent-uptick-in-speakers-study.html%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221204-225951-345560#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: E:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a(:Title: Te Reo Māori:)
