diff:1670194791:1667499608:=72,88d71%0a%3c #foxbegin 221204-225951-345560#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Why Māori Language Will Struggle to Persist Despite Revitalization Efforts %0a%3c -> - johnternullo%0a%3c -> [-04.12.2022 - 14:59-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221204-225951-345560 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Pākehā (non-Māori) children of New Zealand have begun to learn the Māori language in schools with support of the government, which is aiming for at least 150,000 proficient speakers and 1,000,000 speakers at a basic level by the year 2040. According to models, the number of Māori language speakers may actually decline despite these efforts, due to the future lack of qualified teachers. That is, teaching Pākehā people who will not pass down the language in any way may be an inefficient use of resources relative to providing quality language education for nearly all Māori people. However, anyone can contribute to ensuring the language continues to be spoken by learning and using it. Another obstacle to the language's preservation is that a smaller proportion of speakers are under the age of 65, making less certain the future of how widely-used the language will be.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/01/m-ori-language-likely-doomed-despite-recent-uptick-in-speakers-study.html%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221204-225951-345560#%0a
